can you look at the repos in https://github.com/stars/jmur214/lists/trading-machine/ and see if any would add any more real value (still, not ai based)? 

and let’s say we do hit that ceiling, what does that look like? is there any way to make money/leverage the machine in a way to make money outside of just my own return from capital?

# Two-part answer

## Part 1 — Repo audit, non-AI value only

I went through your list. Most are AI-first or low-relevance. The non-AI candidates worth real attention:

### High value — investigate further

**`noterminusgit/statarb`** — *"Production-grade statistical arbitrage system with 20+ alpha strategies and portfolio optimization."*
**If the claim holds**, this is the highest-leverage repo in the list. 20+ alpha strategies + portfolio optimization is potentially years of edge-discovery work. Verify that the strategies are actually working code (not just stubs/markdown), check for survivorship bias / lookahead in the backtest infrastructure, and look at the portfolio-optimization module specifically — that's exactly what your Engine C is missing. **Worth a Saturday afternoon to clone, audit, and steal what's reusable.**

**`ScottfreeLLC/AlphaPy`** — *"Python AutoML tool designed for trading systems and sports betting."*
This is a well-known mature project. **AutoML for trading is exactly what your Feature Foundry needs**, and AlphaPy already wraps tsfresh, scikit-learn, XGBoost, etc. for time-series classification/regression. Probably faster than building from scratch. Likely needs adaptation to your edge interface, but the engineering is real. **High value, low risk.**

**`warproxxx/poly_data`** — *"Polymarket data retrieval tool."*
I specifically called out Polymarket as a free data source for prediction-market features. **A ready-made integration saves you the API research.** Drop into your Feature Foundry as a Tier-B feature source for macro event probabilities (Fed cuts, recession, election outcomes). **Half-day integration, real signal.**

**`je-suis-tm/quant-trading`** — *"Python quantitative trading strategies including pattern recognition and Monte Carlo simulations."*
Community strategy library. Treat it as a **reference / inspiration archive**, not as code to merge. Useful for cross-checking your existing edges against alternative implementations, finding strategy ideas you haven't considered. **Browsing value, not integration value.**

### Medium value — peek but don't depend

**`Fincept-Corporation/FinceptTerminal`** — Finance app with market analytics. Could surface ideas for what to track, but probably duplicates capabilities you have. Worth 30 minutes of browsing.

### Skip — AI-first or low-relevance

- `algo2t/alphatrade` — Indian broker (SAS), wrong platform
- `ginlix-ai/LangAlpha` — AI-first
- `koala73/worldmonitor` — AI-first
- `bloomberg-terminal/bloomberg-terminal-free` — claims "free Bloomberg" almost always overpromise. Skip.
- `gsd-build/gsd-2` — agent dev framework, not trading
- `garrytan/gstack` — Claude Code workflow tools
- `666ghj/MiroFish` — vague, AI-flavored
- `shiyu-coder/Kronos` — financial foundation model, AI
- `0xemmkty/QuantMuse` — AI-flavored
- `virattt/dexter` — AI agent

### Honest summary

Of 16 repos, **2-3 are worth real time** (statarb, AlphaPy, poly_data). The rest are either AI-based (excluded by your constraint), wrong platform, or marginal browsing value. **Star-list quality is mostly low** because the trading-tools space is saturated with AI-flavored projects right now. Don't feel obligated to extract value from all of them.

---

## Part 2 — If you hit the ceiling, what does that look like?

**Realistic ceiling state:** OOS Sharpe ~1.0 net of all costs and taxes, CAGR 12-18% (depending on profile), max drawdown -10% to -15%, autonomous discovery loop producing 1-2 new validated edges per quarter, Moonshot Sleeve catching 1-3 multibaggers per year.

That's a top-1% retail quant outcome. **Now what do you do with it?**

### Path A: Manage other people's money (the obvious one)

**Registered Investment Advisor (RIA)**
- Register with state (under $100M AUM) or SEC (over $100M)
- Form an LLC, set up custodian relationship (Schwab, Fidelity, IB)
- Charge management fee (1-2% AUM annual) + optionally performance fee (typically 15-20% over benchmark)
- Compliance overhead: Form ADV, annual audit, ongoing reporting
- **Realistic ramp:** $1-5M AUM friends/family year 1, $25-50M AUM by year 5 if track record is real

**Realistic income at $25M AUM:**
- 1.5% management fee = $375k/year base
- 15% performance fee on outperformance — variable, often $0-300k
- Total: ~$400-700k/year sustainable

**Hard requirement:** verifiable live track record (audited returns), typically 3+ years before serious money flows.

**Private fund (Reg D 506(b)/(c))**
Higher capacity than RIA SMAs but requires accredited investors only, more legal/audit complexity. Skip unless you're at $50M+ AUM scale.

### Path B: Separately Managed Accounts (SMA) — easier intermediate

Each client opens their own Alpaca / IB account, gives you trading authority, you run the same strategy across all. **Doesn't require fund formation.** Just RIA registration + client agreements.

- Cleaner regulatory profile
- No commingled assets, no audit complexity
- Each client sees their own returns, taxes, holdings
- **Best path for years 2-5** before scaling to fund

Realistic: 10-30 SMAs at $250k-2M each = $5-25M AUM.

### Path C: Newsletter / signal subscription

Substack-style premium subscription publishing daily/weekly signals.

- $50-500/month per subscriber
- 1000 subs × $150/month = **$1.8M/year ARR**
- Lower regulatory bar (you're publishing opinions, not managing money)
- Marketing is the bottleneck — content distribution
- **Capacity-friendly**: subscribers can act on signals at their own size; your strategy doesn't degrade

Genuine quant systems running this model successfully: a handful (Macro Ops, Quantpedia, etc.). Bar is high but doable.

### Path D: License the system to other RIAs / family offices

White-label the signal feed or full architecture to 5-10 small RIAs who lack quant capability.

- $10-50k/month per client
- 10 clients × $25k/month = **$3M/year ARR**
- Higher value-per-customer, B2B sales cycle
- Capacity-managed by limiting client count
- Compliance simpler than running money yourself

This is what some prop firms quietly do — license edges to mid-tier RIAs/wealth managers.

### Path E: Data productization

Discovered features can be productized:
- "Crowding signal" (you'd need to build it)
- "Regime classifier output"
- "Capital-allocation efficiency score"

Sell to prop shops, smaller hedge funds. Realistic: $5-50k/year per customer × 20-50 customers = **$100k-2M/year**.

This is the QuantConnect / Quandl model.

### Path F: Sell or get acqui-hired

5-10 years in, with a real live track record at $50M+ AUM:
- Quant firms acquire small shops with proven edges
- Range: $1M-$25M+ depending on Sharpe, AUM, and IP defensibility
- Or you take an institutional seat at a larger fund (typical: $300k-$1M+ base + bonus)

### Path G: Educational content + course

Document the journey publicly, build an audience, monetize via course/book/speaking.

- Course: $500-2000 one-time × 500 students = $250k-1M one-shot
- Book: $50k-200k typical
- Speaking: $5-25k/talk
- **Mostly builds optionality and credibility for paths A-D**

### Path H: Open source + premium

Open-source the framework (Foundry, gauntlet, governance). Monetize:
- Managed hosting
- Premium edge library
- Support contracts
- Consulting

Lower direct revenue, higher reputational value. Probably $100-500k/year sustainable but builds a community moat.

---

## Realistic 10-year income trajectory

```
Year 1-2:  $0 incremental (own capital trading + system development)
Year 3:    $50-150k    (small RIA, $5-10M AUM, friends/family)
Year 5:    $300-700k   ($25-30M AUM at 1.5% + performance)
Year 7:    $500k-2M    ($50-100M AUM if scaling continues)
Year 10:   $1-10M+     (decision point: stay small / scale fund / sell / license)
```

**The bottleneck isn't the system.** It's:
1. **Live track record** (must accrue over years, can't compress)
2. **AUM acquisition skill** (sales, networking, marketing — different muscle than coding)
3. **Compliance bandwidth** (regulatory work scales with AUM)
4. **Capacity ceiling** (some strategies break above $50M-$500M depending on edge type)

### What you should do now to optionalize

Even if monetization is years away, do these now to keep all paths open:

1. **Register all live trading under a separate LLC** — clean entity for future RIA registration
2. **Audit-ready record-keeping** — every trade decision logged with rationale, every backtest reproducible, every config versioned. **GIPS-compliant performance reporting from day 1 of real money.**
3. **Capacity testing as a routine** — know honestly at what AUM each edge breaks. This determines which path (newsletter? fund? license?) makes sense.
4. **Public-facing content from day 1** — even minimal blog/Substack documenting the journey. Audience is asset; built only by years of consistency.
5. **Don't take any institutional money on handshake deals** — even friends/family. The first dollar of OPM should ideally be after RIA registration.

### The most underrated path

**Pure newsletter (Path C)**, oddly. Reasons:
- Lowest regulatory friction
- Capacity-friendly (subscribers don't crowd your fills)
- Compounds trust over years (your audience IS your asset)
- Optionalizes everything else (newsletter audience converts to fund LPs later)
- Doesn't require giving up own-capital trading

A 20-something with 40 years of horizon could realistically build a $5-50M/year newsletter business while ALSO running their own capital — without ever taking outside money.

### The bigger question

**The most valuable thing the system gives you isn't the dollars per se — it's the option set.** A working autonomous trading system is unusual enough that you can pick which monetization path fits your life: passive own-capital, active fund management, content business, B2B licensing, or sell/exit. Most quants only have one path open. **Building the system right preserves all of them.**

Don't pick a monetization path until year 3 of live track record. **Don't optimize for monetization until then either** — premature optimization for revenue distorts the system. Build the engine. Run real capital. Document everything publicly. **The path will pick itself when the track record is undeniable.**
